entry.title: Add feature to cancel the effect of MainThreadCompositingPriority when WebRTC is used.
entry.content:
There is strong evidence that MainThreadCompositingPriority causes

audio glitches and video cpu adaptation while in a WebRTC call.

Inspection of traces on Windows and MacOS suggest that the main thread

of the renderer hosting the call competes with other threads that are

critical to the quality of the video call.



Disabling MainThreadCompositingPriority entirely is not an ideal

solution, because it would cause serious regressions to Web Vitals.

This CL creates a feature to disable it only for renderers hosting a

WebRTC call. We'll look into more refined solutions over the next

quarter, but in the meantime, having a simple / low-risk solution that

can be merged to higher channels is important.

entry.title: Revert "[BRP] Remove ref-count-size experiment parameter"
entry.content:
This reverts commit 595f2caa00721cd2797de99a28c910c4fb6330b6.



Reason for revert: Suspected perf regression. Unlikely this is casued

by this CL, as it's supposed to be a no-op, but I wanted to test

the change to fieldtrial_testing_config.json in isolation.



Original change's description:

> [BRP] Remove ref-count-size experiment parameter

>

> Assume everywhere that 0 was passed, which means "use natural size".

> This means use sizeof(PartitionRefCount), possibly adjusted to

> workaround certain issues:

> 1) MTE/BRP race (crbug.com/1445816)

> 2) Mac 13 & 14 crashes (crbug.com/1378822, crbug.com/1457756)

> But this calculation happens internally and is unaffected by this CL.

> The only difference is that we can no longer externally override

> ref_count_size to something higher.

>

> This CL is considered a no-op, since the default param size is

> "natural" (i.e. 0).

>

entry.title: [iOS] Use DiffableDataSource for PageInfo table view
entry.content:
This CL updates the PageInfo, to use the DiffableDataSource API

instead of the custom Chrome API.

This change include:

- Using translation between the enum and NSNumber

- Register/dequeue the cells manually

- Handle the header/footer manually

- Handle the cells manually



The main functional change is that the data are now "pulled" when

displayed instead of being stored in the item (i.e. when the Table

View wants to display the cell we look at the value from the

permissionsInfo instead of looking at the permissionsInfo at the

creation time).



This CL is also adding helpers to register/dequeue cell and headers

more easily.

It is also creating a new base class to be able to handle the

empty view and other things if needed in the future.



But on the other end, those changes mean that:

- Reloading the cell is much easier: as the information are looked up

when the TableView is asking for it, the only action is to ask for

the item to be reloaded.

- The Switch delegate is handled at the same time as the switch cell

configuration

entry.title: Fix paint invalidation delay check in LayoutObject::WillRenderImage
entry.content:
Only suspend when paint invalidation is delayed and the object is marked

as needing to check for paint invalidation. When the image that's being

delayed is outside the viewport but end being painted because it's

within the "interest rect" it could otherwise end up in a state where

it is suspended but won't be painted again (lacking other external

stimuli that trigger a paint invalidation).



Fixed: 1513304
